In .NET 10, MAUI adopted Android's **edge-to-edge** display by default, which makes the deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` no longer functional. The modern fix is to react to **keyboard window insets**.

**Recommended approach — handle IME insets in your Android platform code:**

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    // Ensure edge-to-edge + adjustResize are both set
    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);
    Window!.SetSoftInputMode(SoftInput.AdjustResize);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var systemBar = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

        // Push content up by the keyboard height
        v.SetPadding(
            systemBar.Left,
            systemBar.Top,
            systemBar.Right,
            Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, systemBar.Bottom));

        return insets;
    }
}
```

**Alternatively**, if you want a pure-XAML approach, wrap your input bar in a layout that respects safe areas and add a `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect` attribute on the page (to avoid conflicts), then manually listen to keyboard changes via a `CommunityToolkit` behavior or a custom handler.

**Quick summary of what changed:**
| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |
|--------|---------|
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` | Edge-to-edge + IME `WindowInsets` listener |

The insets listener approach is the Android-recommended pattern going forward and works reliably with MAUI's new rendering pipeline.
